(341, 75, 'Those dupes come down to 2 model id''s(mid). \r\nThere are 1288 ''new equipment'' records that have an mid of 3062. \r\n\r\nAnd there are 2322 ''new equipment'' records that have the mid of 3058. \r\n\r\nIn order to correct the situation, we would have to choose one model id as the &quot;keeper&quot; and then hunt down any code that refers to the &quot;other&quot; mid and switch it to the keeper. We''d also have to check all tables that contain an mid value of the ones mentioned and make sure they are all corrected to the &quot;keeper&quot; mid.'),
(342, 67, 'I will be adding &quot;&amp;MachineType=${Node.MachineType}&quot; to the text that is sent to the auto ticket tool. This variable will either contain &quot;Cisco&quot; or &quot;Fortinet&quot;. \r\n\r\nWhat we need to do is change the logic in which the tool creates a ticket. Currently, the tool creates a ticket based on the entire node name. Example, 422GEN102-swi-IDF1-PERIM.westipc.com. What we need to do is create a ticket based on the first few characters, &quot;422GEN102&quot;. If multiple devices go down and they match those first few characters they need to be lumped into the same ticket. These devices should pass the above mentioned varible containing &quot;Cisco&quot;. \r\n\r\nThe one exception is a device such as &quot;422GEN102-fgt-100D&quot;. This will need a ticket created separate regardless of wether a ticket already exists for &quot;422GEN102&quot;. This node will pass the variable that contains &quot;Fortinet&quot;. '),
